   "source": [
    "snapshot_date = df['Invoice_date'].max()                             # Get latest date in dataset (reference point)\n",
    "\n",
    "rfm = df.groupby('Customer_ID').agg({                                # Create RFM metrics\n",
    "    \n",
    "    'Invoice_date': lambda x: (snapshot_date - x.max()).days,        # Recency = days since last purchase\n",
    "                                                        \n",
    "    'Invoice_no': 'count',                                           # Frequency = number of purchases\n",
    "    \n",
    "    'Total_revenue': 'sum'                                           # Monetary = total money spent\n",
    "})\n",
    "\n",
    "rfm.columns = ['Recency', 'Frequency', 'Monetary']                  # Rename columns\n",
    "rfm.head()                                                          # View result"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "699a9381-8eb7-46ee-874b-6870e469599b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
    "scaler = StandardScaler()                                            # Scale data (important for KMeans)\n",
    "rfm_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(rfm)\n",
    "kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42)                       # Create KMeans model with 4 clusters\n",
    "rfm['Cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(rfm_scaled)                      # Assign cluster labels"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "1492cb39-5c45-4e0c-84f9-9caaa51a91c0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 800x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import seaborn as sns                                                # for scatter plot visualisation\n",
    "import matplotlib.ticker as mticker                                  # for formatting y-axis tick labels as £K\n",
    "\n",
    "cluster_map = (rfm.groupby('Cluster')['Monetary']                    # group customers by cluster number\n",
    "               .mean()                                               # calculate average monetary value per cluster\n",
    "               .sort_values(ascending=False)                         # sort highest spenders first — cluster with highest avg spend = Champions\n",
    "               .reset_index())                                       # reset index so cluster numbers become a column\n",
    "\n",
    "label_map = {                                                        # create a dictionary mapping cluster numbers to business-friendly segment names\n",
    "    cluster_map.iloc[0]['Cluster']: 'Champions',                     # highest avg monetary value → Champions\n",
    "    cluster_map.iloc[1]['Cluster']: 'Loyal',                         # second highest → Loyal\n",
    "    cluster_map.iloc[2]['Cluster']: 'At-Risk',                       # third → At-Risk\n",
    "    cluster_map.iloc[3]['Cluster']: 'Hibernating'                    # lowest avg monetary value → Hibernating\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "rfm['Segment'] = rfm['Cluster'].map(label_map)                       # replace cluster numbers with segment labels using the dictionary above\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 5))                               # create figure and axes object\n",
    "\n",
    "sns.scatterplot(data=rfm,                                            # use rfm dataframe\n",
    "                x='Recency', y='Monetary',                           # x = days since last purchase, y = total spend\n",
    "                hue='Segment',                                       # colour each dot by segment name\n",
    "                palette=['#1f77b4','#2ca02c','#ff7f0e','#d62728'],   # distinct colour per segment\n",
    "                s=80,                                                # dot size\n",
    "                ax=ax)                                               # draw on the axes object\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.set_title('Customer Segmentation — RFM Analysis (4 Segments)', fontsize=14)                   # chart title\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Recency (Days Since Last Purchase)', fontsize=12)                                 # x-axis label — clarifies what recency means\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Monetary Value (£)', fontsize=12)                                                 # y-axis label\n",
    "ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(mticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, _: f'£{x/1e3:.0f}K'))               # format y-axis ticks as £K values\n",
    "ax.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.4)                                                         # faint gridlines for readability\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()                                                                               # auto-adjust spacing so nothing overlaps\n",
    "\n",
    "fig.text(0.5, -0.04,\n",
    "         'Each dot is one customer. X-axis shows days since last purchase (lower = more recent). '\n",
    "         'Y-axis shows total spend. Segments assigned by K-Means clustering on Recency, Frequency, and Monetary value.',\n",
    "         ha='center', fontsize=10, color='black', style='italic')                                # business insight footnote explaining chart to non-technical readers\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()                                                                                        # render and display the chart"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2fb402a0-2fec-41b5-a9b3-f43a634b8ecd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Insights obtained\n",
    "\n",
    "**Finding:** Four clear customer segments emerge:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Champions** → bought recently + spend the most → highest-value customers  \n",
    "- **Loyal Customers** → purchase frequently with consistent spend  \n",
    "- **At-Risk** → declining activity, may stop purchasing soon  \n",
    "- **Hibernating** → no purchase for 200+ days + low spend → nearly lost  \n",
    "\n",
    "Champions show low recency and high monetary value, while Hibernating customers \n",
    "contribute minimal revenue and engagement.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why it matters:** A small group of high-value customers drives a large share of \n",
    "revenue. Losing Champions would directly reduce revenue and profitability.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Business Recommendation:**  \n",
    "- Re-engage At-Risk and Hibernating customers with targeted discounts or reminders  \n",
    "- Retain Champions through VIP strategies — early access, exclusive offers, priority benefits  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "794cc2f0-409a-4323-a286-cdf40f2fed0f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Cohort Retention Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "Cohort analysis tracks customer retention by grouping users based on their first \n",
    "purchase month and measuring how many return in subsequent months.\n",
    "\n",
    "This directly answers: **\"Is the business retaining its customers over time?\"**\n",
    "\n",
    "A strong retention curve indicates repeat purchase behaviour and customer loyalty.  \n",
    "A sharp drop-off suggests customers are not returning after their first purchase.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What to look for:**\n",
    "- Stable retention beyond Month 2–3 → healthy repeat behaviour  \n",
    "- Rapid decline after Month 1 → weak engagement or poor customer experience  \n",
    "\n",
    "Low retention may point to issues in product value, pricing, or post-purchase \n",
    "engagement (e.g., lack of follow-up marketing).\n",
    "\n",
    "This analysis highlights when and where customers drop off, enabling targeted \n",
    "interventions to improve repeat purchase rates and long-term revenue."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "29aed4f2-a1b8-4681-9998-fd34ab7524ab",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df['Invoice_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Invoice_date'], errors='coerce')  # Convert Invoice_date to datetime format\n",
    "df = df.dropna(subset=['Invoice_date'])                                  # Drop rows where date is missing\n",
    "\n",
    "                                                                          # First purchase month of each customer\n",
    "df['CohortMonth'] = df.groupby('Customer_ID')['Invoice_date'] \\\n",
    "                     .transform('min').dt.to_period('M')\n",
    "\n",
    "                                                                         # Invoice month\n",
    "df['InvoiceMonth'] = df['Invoice_date'].dt.to_period('M')\n",
    "                                                                         # Extract year and month separately and calculate difference\n",
    "df['CohortIndex'] = (\n",
    "    (df['InvoiceMonth'].dt.year - df['CohortMonth'].dt.year) * 12 +\n",
    "    (df['InvoiceMonth'].dt.month - df['CohortMonth'].dt.month)\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "id": "c556a468-f591-478a-a831-c4dc1a2c2ed2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x500 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import seaborn as sns                                                    # for heatmap visualisation\n",
    "\n",
    "cohort = df.pivot_table(index='CohortMonth', columns='CohortIndex',      # rows = cohort month, columns = months since first purchase\n",
    "                        values='Customer_ID', aggfunc='nunique')         # count unique customers active in each month\n",
    "\n",
    "cohort = cohort.div(cohort.iloc[:, 0], axis=0)                           # divide each row by its month-0 value to convert counts to retention %\n",
    "\n",
    "cohort.index = cohort.index.to_timestamp().strftime('%b %Y')             # convert period index to readable labels e.g. 'Dec 2010'\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))                                  # create figure and axes object\n",
    "\n",
    "sns.heatmap(cohort,                                                      # plot retention % table as a colour heatmap\n",
    "            cmap='Blues',                                                # darker blue = higher retention rate\n",
    "            annot=True, fmt='.0%',                                       # show percentage values inside each cell\n",
    "            linewidths=0.5,                                              # thin lines between cells for readability\n",
    "            cbar_kws={'label': 'Retention Rate'},                        # label the colour bar on the right\n",
    "            ax=ax)                                                       # draw on the axes object\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.set_title('Customer Cohort Retention by First Purchase Month', fontsize=14)                   # chart title\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Months Since First Purchase', fontsize=12)                                        # x-axis label — clarifies what each column represents\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Cohort Month', fontsize=12)                                                       # y-axis label — clarifies what each row represents\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()                                                                               # auto-adjust spacing so nothing overlaps\n",
    "\n",
    "fig.text(0.5, -0.04,\n",
    "         'Dec 2010 cohort shows strongest retention (~30% at Month 6).',\n",
    "         ha='center', fontsize=9, color='navy')                                                  # highlight the single most important finding for quick readers\n",
    "\n",
    "fig.text(0.5, -0.10,\n",
    "         \"Each row is a group of customers who made their first purchase in that month.\\n\"\n",
    "         \"Column 0 = 100% (their first month). Subsequent columns show the % who returned. \"\n",
    "         \"Darker blue = higher retention.\",\n",
    "         ha='center', fontsize=10, color='black', style='italic')                                # business insight footnote explaining how to read the heatmap\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()                                                                                       # render and display the chart"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "65829b27-b4ea-4cde-ba95-7457af55f309",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Insights \n",
    "\n",
    "**Finding:** The December 2010 cohort shows the strongest retention, maintaining \n",
    "over 30% return rate by month 6. Most other cohorts drop sharply after month 1, \n",
    "indicating one-time purchase behaviour.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why it matters:** Early drop-off limits customer lifetime value and increases \n",
    "reliance on new customer acquisition for revenue growth.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Business Recommendation:** Implement a post-purchase engagement strategy targeting \n",
    "the first 30 days. Trigger email campaigns 7 days after purchase with product \n",
    "recommendations, usage tips, or limited-time offers to improve repeat purchase rates."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b292460a-3227-40ca-ba6e-d20d21d584e0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Revenue Forecasting\n",
    "\n",
    "Revenue forecasting is used to estimate short-term sales trends and support \n",
    "data-driven planning decisions.\n",
    "\n",
    "A 3-month moving average is applied to smooth short-term fluctuations and \n",
    "highlight the underlying revenue trend.\n",
    "\n",
    "This provides a clear directional signal for:\n",
    "- Inventory planning and stock allocation  \n",
    "- Budget forecasting and revenue targets  \n",
    "- Identifying seasonal patterns and demand shifts  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "id": "8ab8047c-dbe5-4ce1-b874-8a5b45a7559c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.ticker as mticker                                                  # For axis formatting\n",
    "\n",
    "                                                                                     # Monthly revenue + 3-month moving average\n",
    "monthly_rev = df.groupby('Month_short')['Total_revenue'].sum()                       # Aggregate monthly revenue\n",
    "trend = monthly_rev.rolling(3).mean()                                                # 3-month moving average (trend line)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))                                                           # Create figure\n",
    "\n",
    "                                                                                     # Actual revenue\n",
    "plt.plot(monthly_rev.index, monthly_rev.values,\n",
    "         color='#1B3A6B', marker='o', label='Actual Revenue')  # Navy line\n",
    "\n",
    "                                                                                     # Trend line (NOT forecast)\n",
    "plt.plot(trend.index, trend.values,\n",
    "         color='#E24B4A', linestyle='--', label='3-Month Moving Avg')  # Orange dashed\n",
    "\n",
    "                                                                                     # Labels (fixed)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Month (Dec 2010 – Dec 2011)')                                            # Clear time range\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Total Revenue (£)')                                                      # Proper units\n",
    "\n",
    "                                                                                     # Format Y-axis in millions\n",
    "plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter(\n",
    "    mticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, _: f'£{x/1e6:.1f}M')\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.legend()                                                                        # Show legend\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title('Monthly Revenue Trend with 3-Month Moving Average', fontsize=14)          # Add title\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.4)                                            # Clean grid\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()                                                                   # Layout adjustment\n",
    "plt.figtext(0.5, -0.04,\n",
    "    \"Solid line shows actual monthly revenue. Dashed line is the 3-month moving average, \"\n",
    "    \"which smooths short-term fluctuations to reveal the underlying trend.\\n\"\n",
    "    \"The first two months (Jan, Feb) show actual revenue only, the moving average line starts \"\n",
    "    \"from March onwards, as it needs three months of data to produce its first value.\",\n",
    "    ha='center', fontsize=10, color='black', style='italic')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2640caa8-1f74-4fa3-8415-35fb19758217",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Insights Obtained\n",
    "\n",
    "**Finding:** Revenue increases steadily from September to December, peaking at \n",
    "£1.51M in November. The moving average confirms a consistent seasonal pattern \n",
    "rather than a one-time spike.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why it matters:** Q4 (Sep–Dec) contributes ~45% of total annual revenue, making \n",
    "it the most critical period for business performance. Poor preparation directly \n",
    "impacts revenue outcomes.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Business Recommendation:**  \n",
    "- Increase inventory procurement by August to meet peak demand  \n",
    "- Launch Q4 marketing campaigns by mid-September  \n",
    "- Prioritise Champions and high-frequency customers for early targeting  "
   ]
  },
